 :tx/rationale "ASSESSMENT: The Deepest Question — Type 9 Divergence. Is the system observing its own failure to converge? The project's bedrock claim: it implements the atomic operation at every level (observe reality → compare to model → reduce the discrepancy). But the system's most important discrepancy — F(S) stagnant at 0.62 for 13 sessions, hypothesis ledger degrading, 265 untested INVs accumulating — is not being detected, diagnosed, or reduced by the system itself. A human reading the status dashboard sees these numbers. But the guidance system does not emit 'your verification pipeline is the bottleneck.' The routing function does not prioritize verification tasks over new feature tasks when the spec-impl gap is widening. The harvest does not capture 'F(S) has not moved in 5 sessions — this is anomalous.' If Braid is truly a learning system, it should detect its own stagnation as Type 9 divergence (Reflexive: system vs system's-model-of-itself) and recommend the verification sprint. If it cannot — if an external assessment must identify the obvious — then the self-improvement loop (the Y-combinator property) is not yet operational. THE TEST: Run braid status and braid seed --task 'improve convergence' and check whether the system recommends what this assessment recommends. If it does: the system is learning. If not: the most important invariant — the system can diagnose its own convergence failures — is untested and possibly violated. This is the only divergence type that matters at this stage. VERIFICATION: Implement Type 9 detection: an anomaly detector that fires when F(S) is flat for N sessions, or hypothesis mean error exceeds threshold, or untested INV count exceeds threshold. Wire into guidance footer as priority signal. TRACES TO: SEED.md §6 (8-type divergence taxonomy + Type 9), ADR-FOUNDATION-014, C7 (self-bootstrap)."
